TY  - JOUR
AU  - Bianchi, Francesco
AU  - Gómez-Cram, Roberto
AU  - Kung, Howard
T1  - Using Social Media to Identify the Effects of Congressional Viewpoints on Asset Prices
PY  - 2024
Y1  - 2024/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhae001
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 37
IS  - 7
SP  - 2244
EP  - 2272
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - We use a high-frequency identification approach to document that individual politicians affect asset prices. We exploit the regular flow of viewpoints contained in Congress members’ tweets. Supportive (critical) tweets increase (decrease) the stock prices of the targeted firm and the corresponding industry in minutes around the tweet. The bulk of the stock price effects is concentrated in the tweets revealing news about future legislative action. The effects are amplified around committee meeting days, especially when the tweet originates from committee members and influential politicians. Overall, we show that Congress members’ social media accounts are an important source of political news.
Y2  - 8/18/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhae001
ER  - 



